{"title_page": "Coping Mechanisms", "text_new": "{{for|managing stress|Coping (psychology)}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Coping Mechanisms\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Si Schroeder]]\n| cover      = CopingMechanismsVinyl - from Commons.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Vinyl cover\n| released   =people started to stink and thats when coping mechanism happened\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]] <br/> [[Electronic music]] <br/> [[Experimental music]]\n| length     = 48:00\n| label      = [http://Trust%20Me%20I'm%20A%20Thief Trust Me I'm A Thief]\n| producer   = Jimmy Eadie\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Coping Mechanisms''''' is the debut album by [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[music artist]] [[Si Schroeder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/theticket/2006/0505/1146660071470.html|title=CD of the week|publisher=The Irish Times|date=2006-05-05}}</ref> It was released in 2006 by [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[independent record label]] [http://www.trustmeimathief.com Trust Me I'm A Thief].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustmeimathief.com/artists/schroeders.html |title=Si Schroeder: artist profile |publisher=Trust Me I'm A Thief |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717105224/http://www.trustmeimathief.com/artists/schroeders.html |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Irish Times]]'' at the time of its release [[Si Schroeder]] explained that the title 'comes from observing how friends and colleagues of his deal with living in 21st-century [[Dublin]]. \"The nature of living in [[Dublin]] has definitely influenced the themes on this record. There's no doubt that it has become increasingly difficult to live here, so people use mechanisms and quirks to cope with living here and staying sane.\"'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/theticket/2006/0512/1146660074478.html|title=Si-CHEDELIA|publisher=The Irish Times|date=2006-05-05}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n''Coping Mechanisms'' was shortlisted for the 2006 [[Choice Music Prize]] Irish album of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.choicemusicprize.com/past_prizes_2006.html|title=Choice Music Prize 2006 Shortlist|publisher=Choice Music Prize}}</ref>\n\nInfluential Irish [[blog]]ger [http://www.nialler9.com Nialler9] named ''Coping Mechanisms'' his [[blog]]'s No 1 Irish album of 2006, as did the influential ''[[Foggy Notions]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nialler9.com/2006/12/dance-electronic/top-irish-albums-of-2006-the-results |title=Top Irish Albums of 2006 - The Results 1. Si Schroeder - Coping Mechanisms |publisher=Nialler9.com |date=2006-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114043113/http://www.nialler9.com/2006/12/dance-electronic/top-irish-albums-of-2006-the-results/ |archivedate=2011-01-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/mystery-man-comes-out-to-play-the-sweet-sounds-of-a-best-kept-secret-64712.html|title=Si Schroeder: Mystery man comes out to play the sweet sounds of a best kept secret...|publisher=The Irish Independent|date=2006-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspace.com/sischroeder|title=Si Schroeder Bio|publisher=MySpace}}</ref>\n\nIrish music magazine ''[[Hot Press]]'' scored the album 9/10 in its review and includes ''Coping Mechanisms'' in its list of '250 Greatest Irish Albums of All Time' voted for by more than 200 of Ireland's leading musicians and published in December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.ie/music/reviews/albums/2866379.html|title=We're all part of the cope show|publisher=Hot Press|date=2006-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pub37.bravenet.com/forum/static/show.php?usernum=3172289350&frmid=7238&msgid=1030521&cmd=show|title=Hot Press (Ireland) - 250 Greatest Irish Albums Of All Time|publisher=The Old Acclaimed Music Forum, Bravenet.com|date=2010-01-21}}</ref>\n\nIrish music journalist Tony Clayton-Lea includes ''Coping Mechanisms'' in his 2011 book ''101 Irish Records You Must Hear Before You Die''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thumped.com/interviews/tony-clayton-lea-joining-the-dots.html?showall=1|title=Tony Clayton-Lea - Joining The Dots|publisher=Thumped.com|date=2011-11-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130630114418/http://thumped.com/interviews/tony-clayton-lea-joining-the-dots.html?showall=1|archivedate=2013-06-30}}</ref>\n\nInfluential [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[blog]] [http://hardcorefornerds.blogspot.com/2009/02/slowcoreshoegazespringtime-post-si.html Hardcore for Nerds] called ''Coping Mechanisms'' [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland's]] ''[[Spiderland]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardcorefornerds.blogspot.com/2009/02/slowcoreshoegazespringtime-post-si.html|title=Si Schroeder: Coping Mechanisms|publisher=Hardcore for Nerds on Blogspot|date=2009-02-18}}</ref>\n\n[[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] music website [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123551/http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 Drop-D] described ''Coping Mechanisms'' as \"a record that can creep inside of you to massage your soul... the album isn't electronic in the strictest sense; the pallet containing a balance between electronic and organic sounds, not to mention some of the strangest samples you're likely to hear\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 |title=Come on over to Schroeder |publisher=Drop-d.ie |date=2006-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123551/http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n# {{YouTube|JXy8En1UJIQ|The Reluctant Aviator}}\n# Lavendermist\n# C4\n# {{YouTube|DTFtQOTtcns|Eyes-wide}}\n# (Apology)\n# Elaine's Porsche/ Poor H\u00e9l\u00e8ne/ C\u00e9line Pours\n# {{YouTube|o8ADrausgnk|Duck!}}\n# {{YouTube|BYeYJR1BXDM|A Little More}}\n# Here, After\n\nThe CD album ends with an unnamed hidden track. The vinyl album omits track 5 (Apology).\n\n{{Listen|filename=C4 clip.ogg|title=''C4''|description=A clip from ''Coping Mechanisms'' track ''C4''|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n== Personnel==\n* [[Si Schroeder]]: guitars, vocals, MPC4K, percussion, zither, wineglass\n* Bryan O'Connell: drums, percussion, triangle, beergoggle\n* John McMahon: bass harmonics on ''A Little More'', scanner, spiritvessel\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Si-Schroeder/33542298272 Official Si Schroeder Facebook page]\n*[https://twitter.com Si Schroeder is on Twitter as @sischroeder]\n*[https://www.myspace.com/sischroeder Official Si Schroeder Myspace page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110717105224/http://www.trustmeimathief.com/artists/schroeders.html Si Schroeder on Trust Me I'm A Thief]\n*[http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/theticket/2006/0505/1146660071470.html ''Coping Mechanisms'' review in The Irish Times]\n*[http://www.hotpress.ie/music/reviews/albums/2866379.html ''Coping Mechanisms'' review in Hot Press magazine]\n\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Si Schroeder albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|managing stress|Coping (psychology)}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Coping Mechanisms\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Si Schroeder]]\n| cover      = CopingMechanismsVinyl - from Commons.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Vinyl cover\n| released   =\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]] <br/> [[Electronic music]] <br/> [[Experimental music]]\n| length     = 48:00\n| label      = [http://Trust%20Me%20I'm%20A%20Thief Trust Me I'm A Thief]\n| producer   = Jimmy Eadie\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Coping Mechanisms''''' is the debut album by [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[music artist]] [[Si Schroeder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/theticket/2006/0505/1146660071470.html|title=CD of the week|publisher=The Irish Times|date=2006-05-05}}</ref> It was released in 2006 by [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[independent record label]] [http://www.trustmeimathief.com Trust Me I'm A Thief].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustmeimathief.com/artists/schroeders.html |title=Si Schroeder: artist profile |publisher=Trust Me I'm A Thief |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717105224/http://www.trustmeimathief.com/artists/schroeders.html |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Irish Times]]'' at the time of its release [[Si Schroeder]] explained that the title 'comes from observing how friends and colleagues of his deal with living in 21st-century [[Dublin]]. \"The nature of living in [[Dublin]] has definitely influenced the themes on this record. There's no doubt that it has become increasingly difficult to live here, so people use mechanisms and quirks to cope with living here and staying sane.\"'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/theticket/2006/0512/1146660074478.html|title=Si-CHEDELIA|publisher=The Irish Times|date=2006-05-05}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n''Coping Mechanisms'' was shortlisted for the 2006 [[Choice Music Prize]] Irish album of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.choicemusicprize.com/past_prizes_2006.html|title=Choice Music Prize 2006 Shortlist|publisher=Choice Music Prize}}</ref>\n\nInfluential Irish [[blog]]ger [http://www.nialler9.com Nialler9] named ''Coping Mechanisms'' his [[blog]]'s No 1 Irish album of 2006, as did the influential ''[[Foggy Notions]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nialler9.com/2006/12/dance-electronic/top-irish-albums-of-2006-the-results |title=Top Irish Albums of 2006 - The Results 1. Si Schroeder - Coping Mechanisms |publisher=Nialler9.com |date=2006-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114043113/http://www.nialler9.com/2006/12/dance-electronic/top-irish-albums-of-2006-the-results/ |archivedate=2011-01-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/mystery-man-comes-out-to-play-the-sweet-sounds-of-a-best-kept-secret-64712.html|title=Si Schroeder: Mystery man comes out to play the sweet sounds of a best kept secret...|publisher=The Irish Independent|date=2006-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspace.com/sischroeder|title=Si Schroeder Bio|publisher=MySpace}}</ref>\n\nIrish music magazine ''[[Hot Press]]'' scored the album 9/10 in its review and includes ''Coping Mechanisms'' in its list of '250 Greatest Irish Albums of All Time' voted for by more than 200 of Ireland's leading musicians and published in December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.ie/music/reviews/albums/2866379.html|title=We're all part of the cope show|publisher=Hot Press|date=2006-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pub37.bravenet.com/forum/static/show.php?usernum=3172289350&frmid=7238&msgid=1030521&cmd=show|title=Hot Press (Ireland) - 250 Greatest Irish Albums Of All Time|publisher=The Old Acclaimed Music Forum, Bravenet.com|date=2010-01-21}}</ref>\n\nIrish music journalist Tony Clayton-Lea includes ''Coping Mechanisms'' in his 2011 book ''101 Irish Records You Must Hear Before You Die''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thumped.com/interviews/tony-clayton-lea-joining-the-dots.html?showall=1|title=Tony Clayton-Lea - Joining The Dots|publisher=Thumped.com|date=2011-11-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130630114418/http://thumped.com/interviews/tony-clayton-lea-joining-the-dots.html?showall=1|archivedate=2013-06-30}}</ref>\n\nInfluential [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[blog]] [http://hardcorefornerds.blogspot.com/2009/02/slowcoreshoegazespringtime-post-si.html Hardcore for Nerds] called ''Coping Mechanisms'' [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland's]] ''[[Spiderland]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardcorefornerds.blogspot.com/2009/02/slowcoreshoegazespringtime-post-si.html|title=Si Schroeder: Coping Mechanisms|publisher=Hardcore for Nerds on Blogspot|date=2009-02-18}}</ref>\n\n[[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] music website [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123551/http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 Drop-D] described ''Coping Mechanisms'' as \"a record that can creep inside of you to massage your soul... the album isn't electronic in the strictest sense; the pallet containing a balance between electronic and organic sounds, not to mention some of the strangest samples you're likely to hear\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 |title=Come on over to Schroeder |publisher=Drop-d.ie |date=2006-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123551/http://www.drop-d.ie/legacy-1128/1472 |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n# {{YouTube|JXy8En1UJIQ|The Reluctant Aviator}}\n# Lavendermist\n# C4\n# {{YouTube|DTFtQOTtcns|Eyes-wide}}\n# (Apology)\n# Elaine's Porsche/ Poor H\u00e9l\u00e8ne/ C\u00e9line Pours\n# {{YouTube|o8ADrausgnk|Duck!}}\n# {{YouTube|BYeYJR1BXDM|A Little More}}\n# Here, After\n\nThe CD album ends with an unnamed hidden track. The vinyl album omits track 5 (Apology).\n\n{{Listen|filename=C4 clip.ogg|title=''C4''|description=A clip from ''Coping Mechanisms'' track ''C4''|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n== Personnel==\n* [[Si Schroeder]]: guitars, vocals, MPC4K, percussion, zither, wineglass\n* Bryan O'Connell: drums, percussion, triangle, beergoggle\n* John McMahon: bass harmonics on ''A Little More'', scanner, spiritvessel\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Si-Schroeder/33542298272 Official Si Schroeder Facebook page]\n*[https://twitter.com Si Schroeder is on Twitter as @sischroeder]\n*[https://www.my