{"title_page": "Lister Hospital, Chelsea", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Lister Hospital\n| org/group   = [[Hospital Corporation of America]]\n| logo        = \n| image       = Chelsea Bridge Road, London.JPG\n| caption     = Lister Hospital\n| map_type    =United Kingdom London Kensington and Chelsea\n| map_caption =Location in Kensington and Chelsea\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.4863|-0.1502|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM|display=inline,title}}\n| location    = [[Chelsea Bridge Road]]\n| region      = [[London]]\n| state       = [[England]]\n| country     = [[United Kingdom]]  <!--needed for infobox-->\n| healthcare  = [[Hospital Corporation of America]]\n| type        = \n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = <!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, CA/US: I/II/III for Trauma certification level -->\n| affiliation = <!-- Medical School and University affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| beds        = 63\n| founded     = 1985\n| closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.thelisterhospital.com/}}\n| other_links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n \nThe '''Lister Hospital''' in Chelsea is a [[private hospital]] in [[Chelsea Bridge Road]], London. It is owned by the [[Hospital Corporation of America]], the largest private operator of health care facilities in the world, and so is not part of the [[National Health Service]] (NHS).\n\n==History==\nOpened in 1985,<ref name=history>{{cite web|url= http://www.thelisterhospital.com/about-us/history-of-the-lister-hospital/ |title=History|publisher=The Lister Hospital|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> the hospital occupies the former premises of the [[Lister Institute of Preventive Medicine]]; both were named in honour of [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister]], a British surgeon considered to be the pioneer of [[aseptic surgery]].<ref name=history/> It has 57 beds in inpatient wards on three floors and a six-bedded Critical Care Unit and specialises in orthopaedics, gynaecology, dermatology, gastroenterology, ophthalmology and plastic surgery, and also runs a fertility clinic.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thelisterhospital.com/about-us/|title=About us|publisher=The Lister Hospital|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> It generates revenue per bed of circa \u00a31 million a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rich overseas patients help private hospitals beat recession|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c354cf36-dd2d-11e4-a772-00144feab7de.html#axzz3jivM6Rqr|accessdate=24 August 2015|publisher=Financial Times|date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n* {{official website | http://www.thelisterhospital.com }}\n* [http://www.cqc.org.uk/location/1-126955884 CQC report]\n \n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in London]]\n[[Category:Health in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Hospital Corporation of America]]\n[[Category:Private hospitals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1985]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Lister Hospital\n| org/group   = [[Hospital Corporation of America]]\n| logo        = \n| image       = Chelsea Bridge Road, London.JPG\n| caption     = Lister Hospital\n| map_type    =United Kingdom London Kensington and Chelsea\n| map_caption =Location in Kensington and Chelsea\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.4863|-0.1502|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM|display=inline,title}}\n| location    = [[Chelsea Bridge Road]]\n| region      = [[London]]\n| state       = [[England]]\n| country     = [[United Kingdom]]  <!--needed for infobox-->\n| healthcare  = [[Hospital Corporation of America]]\n| type        = \n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = <!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, CA/US: I/II/III for Trauma certification level -->\n| affiliation = <!-- Medical School and University affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| beds        = 63\n| founded     = 1985\n| closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.thelisterhospital.com/}}\n| other_links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n \nThe '''Lister Hospital''' in Chelsea is a [[private hospital]] in [[Chelsea Bridge Road]], London. It is owned by the [[Hospital Corporation of America]], the largest private operator of health care facilities in the world, and so is not part of the [[National Health Service]] (NHS).\n\n==History==\nOpened in 1985,<ref name=history>{{cite web|url= http://www.thelisterhospital.com/about-us/history-of-the-lister-hospital/ |title=History|publisher=The Lister Hospital|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> the hospital occupies the former premises of the [[Lister Institute of Preventive Medicine]]; both were named in honour of [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister]], a British surgeon considered to be the pioneer of [[aseptic surgery]].<ref name=history/> It has 57 beds in inpatient wards on three floors and a six-bedded Critical Care Unit and specialises in orthopaedics, gynaecology, dermatology, gastroenterology, ophthalmology and plastic surgery, and also runs a fertility clinic.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thelisterhospital.com/about-us/|title=About us|publisher=The Lister Hospital|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> It generates revenue per bed of circa \u00a31 million a year. <ref>{{cite news|title=Rich overseas patients help private hospitals beat recession|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c354cf36-dd2d-11e4-a772-00144feab7de.html#axzz3jivM6Rqr|accessdate=24 August 2015|publisher=Financial Times|date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n* {{official website | http://www.thelisterhospital.com }}\n* [http://www.cqc.org.uk/location/1-126955884 CQC report]\n \n[[Category:Hospitals in London]]\n[[Category:Health in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Hospital Corporation of America]]\n[[Category:Private hospitals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1985]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lister_Hospital,_Chelsea"}
{"title_page": "July 18", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[477 BC]] &ndash; [[Battle of the Cremera]] as part of the [[Roman\u2013Etruscan_Wars#The_Fabian_war_with_Veii_in_483-476_BC|Roman\u2013Etruscan Wars]].  [[Veii]] ambushes and defeats the [[Roman Republic|Roman]] army.<ref>Livy, VI.1; Plutarch, Camillus IX; Tacitus, Histories II.91; [[Ovid]] gives a different date of 13 February in the Fasti, II.195-6</ref>\n*[[387 BC]]<ref>An alternative year of 390 BC was traditionally favoured</ref> &ndash; [[Roman Republic|Roman]]-[[Gaulish language|Gaulish]] Wars: [[Battle of the Allia]]: A Roman army is defeated by raiding [[Gauls]], leading to the subsequent sacking of [[Ancient Rome|Rome]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Andres Furger|author2=Andres Furger-Gunti|author3=Maria Angelica Borrello|author4=Felix M\u00fcller|title=Helvetian gold: Celtic treasures from Switzerland : exhibition catalogue|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zns7AQAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Swiss National Museum}}</ref>\n* [[362]] &ndash; [[Roman\u2013Persian Wars]]: Emperor [[Julian (emperor)|Julian]] arrives at [[Antioch]] with a Roman expeditionary force (60,000 men) and stays there for nine months to launch a campaign against the [[Sasanian Empire|Persian Empire]].\n* [[452]] &ndash; [[Sack of Aquileia]]: After an earlier [[Battle of the Catalaunian Plains|defeat on the Catalaunian Plains]], [[Attila]] lays siege to the metropolis of [[Aquileia]] and eventually destroys it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Byzantinoslavica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lEdoAAAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Academia|page=66}}</ref>\n* [[645]] &ndash; Chinese forces under general [[Li Shiji]] besiege the strategic fortress city of [[Anshan|Anshi]] ([[Liaoning]]) during the [[Goguryeo\u2013Tang War]].\n*[[1195]] &ndash; [[Battle of Alarcos]]: [[Almohad Caliphate|Almohad]] forces defeat the [[Kingdom of Castile|Castilian]] army of [[Alfonso VIII of Castile|Alfonso VIII]] and force its retreat to [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]].\n*[[1290]] &ndash; King [[Edward I of England]] issues the [[Edict of Expulsion]], banishing all Jews (numbering about 16,000) from England; this was [[Tisha B'Av]] on the [[Hebrew calendar]], a day that commemorates many Jewish calamities.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Chazan|title=The Jews of Medieval Western Christendom: 1000\u20131500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PbYAFkp8rPQC&pg=PA166|date=23 November 2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-45987-7|pages=166}}</ref>\n*[[1334]] &ndash; The bishop of [[Florence]] blesses the first foundation stone for the new ''[[Bell tower|campanile]]'' (bell tower) of the [[Florence Cathedral]], designed by the artist [[Giotto|Giotto di Bondone]].<ref>{{cite book|author=G. Fattorusso|title=Wonders of Italy: the monuments of antiquity, the churches, the palaces, the treasures of art, a handbook for students and travellers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wqcZAQAAMAAJ|year=1930|publisher=G. Fattorusso|page=215}}</ref>\n*[[1389]] &ndash; [[Kingdom of France|France]] and [[Kingdom of England|England]] agree to the [[Truce of Leulinghem]], inaugurating a 13-year peace, the longest period of sustained peace during the [[Hundred Years' War]].\n*[[1391]] &ndash; [[Tokhtamysh\u2013Timur war]]: [[Battle of the Kondurcha River]]: [[Timur]] defeats [[Tokhtamysh]] of the [[Golden Horde]] in present-day southeast Russia.\n*[[1507]] &ndash; In [[Brussels]], [[Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor#Burgundy_and_the_Low_Countries|Prince Charles I]], is crowned [[Burgundian_Netherlands#Rulers|Duke of Burgundy and Count of Flanders]]<ref name=\"State2015\">{{cite book|author=Paul F. State|title=Historical Dictionary of Brussels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fj19CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA100|date=16 April 2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-8108-7921-8|page=100}}</ref>, a year after inheriting the title.\n*[[1555]] &ndash; The [[College of Arms]] is reincorporated by [[Royal charter]] signed by Queen [[Mary I of England]] and King [[Philip II of Spain]].\n*[[1806]] &ndash; A [[1806 Birgu polverista explosion|gunpowder magazine explosion]] in [[Birgu]], [[Malta Protectorate|Malta]], kills around 200 people.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bulletin, Volume 57, Issue 225 \u2013 Volume 58, Issue 232|date=2006|publisher=Military Historical Society (Great Britain)|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=dDNVAAAAYAAJ|page=147|ref=hv}}</ref>\n*[[1812]] &ndash; The [[Treaty of Orebro|Treaties of Orebro]] end both the [[Anglo-Russian War (1807\u201312)|Anglo-Russian]] and [[Anglo-Swedish War (1810\u201312)|Anglo-Swedish Wars]].<ref>{{cite book|author=United States. Dept. of State|title=Catalogue of Treaties, 1814-1918|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T5oLAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA456|year=1919|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=456}}</ref>\n*[[1841]] &ndash; Coronation of Emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil]].<ref>{{cite book|author=D. P. KIDDER, J. C. FLETCHER|title=Brazil and the Brazilians|url=https://archive.org/details/brazilandbrazil01fletgoog|year=1857|pages=[https://archive.org/details/brazilandbrazil01fletgoog/page/n626 592]}}</ref>\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Louis Faidherbe]], French [[governor of Senegal]], arrives to relieve French forces at [[Kayes]], effectively ending El Hajj [[El Hadj Umar Tall|Umar Tall]]'s war against the French.\n*[[1862]] &ndash; First ascent of [[Dent Blanche]], one of the highest summits in the Alps.\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Second Battle of Fort Wagner]]: One of the first formal [[African American]] military units, the [[54th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]], supported by several white regiments, attempts an unsuccessful assault on [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]]-held [[Fort Wagner|Battery Wagner]].\n*[[1870]] &ndash; The [[First Vatican Council]] decrees the dogma of [[papal infallibility]].\n*[[1872]] &ndash; The [[Ballot Act 1872]] in the United Kingdom introduced the requirement that parliamentary and local government elections be held by secret ballot.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hanham |first1=H. J. |title=The Nineteenth-Century Constitution 1815-1914: Documents and Commentary |date=1969 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-09560-0 |page=277 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z0xHM3jmnAUC&pg=PA277 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[1914]] &ndash; The [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] forms the [[Aviation Section, U.S. Signal Corps]], giving official status to aircraft within the U.S. Army for the first time.\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[Adolf Hitler]] publishes ''[[Mein Kampf]]''.\n*[[1936]] &ndash; On the [[Spanish_coup_of_July_1936#Beginning_of_the_coup|Spanish mainland]], a faction of the army supported by [[Fascism_in_Europe#Foreign_affairs|fascists]], rises up against the [[Second Spanish Republic]] in a [[Spanish_coup_of_July_1936|coup d'etat]]<ref name=\"Thomas (1961). p. 126\">{{cite book|last=Thomas |first=Hugh |title=The Spanish Civil War |authorlink=Hugh Thomas (writer)|year=2001 |location=London |publisher=Eyre and Spottiswoode |edition=1st|oclc=395987}}</ref> starting the 3-year-long [[Spanish_Civil_War|Civil War]], resulting in the [[Francoist_Spain|longest dictatorship in modern European history]].\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: During the [[Beisfjord massacre]] in Norway, 15 Norwegian paramilitary guards help members of the SS to kill 288 political prisoners from Yugoslavia.  \n* 1942 &ndash; The Germans test fly the [[Messerschmitt Me 262]] using its [[Junkers Jumo 004|jet engine]]s for the first time.\n*[[1944]] &ndash; World War II: [[Hideki T\u014dj\u014d]] resigns as [[Prime Minister of Japan]] because of numerous setbacks in the war effort.\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Human spaceflight]]: [[Gemini 10]] is launched from [[Cape Canaveral|Cape Kennedy]] on a 70-hour mission that includes docking with an orbiting [[Agena target vehicle]].\n*  1966   &ndash; A racially charged incident in a bar sparks the six-day [[Hough riots]] in [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]]; 1,700 [[Ohio National Guard]] troops intervene to restore order.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Intel]] is founded in [[Mountain View, California]].\n*[[1976]] &ndash; [[Nadia Com\u0103neci]] becomes the first person in [[Olympic Games]] history to score a perfect 10 in [[gymnastics]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].\n*[[1982]] &ndash; Two hundred sixty-eight [[Guatemala]]n ''campesinos'' (\"[[peasant]]s\" or \"country people\") are slain in the [[Plan de S\u00e1nchez massacre]].\n*[[1984]] &ndash; [[San Ysidro McDonald's massacre|McDonald's massacre]] in [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro, California]]: In a fast-food restaurant, James Oliver Huberty opens fire, killing 21 people and injuring 19 others before being shot dead by police.\n*[[1992]] &ndash; A picture of [[Les Horribles Cernettes]] was taken, which became the first ever photo posted to the [[World Wide Web]].\n*[[1994]] &ndash; The [[AMIA bombing|bombing]] of the [[Asociaci\u00f3n Mutual Israelita Argentina]] (Argentine Jewish Community Center) in [[Buenos Aires]] kills 85 people (mostly Jewish) and injures 300.\n*  1994   &ndash; [[Rwandan genocide]]: The [[Rwandan Patriotic Front]] takes control of [[Gisenyi]] and north western [[Rwanda]], forcing the interim government into [[Zaire]] and ending the genocide.\n*[[1995]] &ndash; On the Caribbean island of [[Montserrat]], the [[Soufri\u00e8re Hills]] volcano erupts. Over the course of several years, it devastates the island, destroying the capital, forcing most of the population to flee.\n* [[1996]] &ndash; Storms provoke [[Saguenay flood|severe flooding]] on the [[Saguenay River]], beginning one of [[Quebec]]'s costliest [[natural disaster]]s ever.\n*  1996   &ndash; [[Battle of Mullaitivu (1996)|Battle of Mullaitivu]]: The [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] capture the [[Sri Lanka Army]]'s base, killing over 1200 soldiers.\n*[[2012]] &ndash; At least seven people are killed and 32 others are injured after a [[2012 Burgas bus bombing|bomb explodes]] on an [[Israelis|Israeli]] tour bus at [[Burgas Airport]], [[Bulgaria]]. \n*[[2013]] &ndash; The [[Government of Detroit]], with up to $20 billion in debt, files for the [[Detroit bankruptcy|largest municipal bankruptcy]] in U.S. history.\n*[[2019]] &ndash; A man [[Kyoto Animation arson attack|sets fire to an anime studio]] in [[Fushimi-ku, Kyoto]], [[Japan]], killing at 35 people and injuring dozens of others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/18/dead-suspected-arson-attack-kyoto-animation-japan  |title=Kyoto Animation studio fire: at least 33 dead after arson attack in Japan |newspaper=The Guardian|date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref name=\"livedoor_20190910_deathcount\">{{cite web |url=https://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/16840489/ |script-title=ja:\u4eac\u30a2\u30cb\u653e\u706b\u6bba\u4eba\u3001\u6b7b\u800535\u4eba\u306b |date=2019-07-27 |work=[[Kyodo News]] |language=ja |access-date=10 September 2019 |archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20190910121738/https://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/16840489/ |archive-date=10 September 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n*[[1013]] &ndash; [[Hermann of Reichenau]], German composer, mathematician, and astronomer (b. 1013)<ref>{{cite web |title=Hermann Von Reichenau {{!}} German scholar |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hermann-von-Reichenau |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[1501]] &ndash; [[Isabella of Austria]], queen of Denmark (d. 1526)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Terjanian |first1=Pierre |title=The Last Knight: The Art, Armor, and Ambition of Maximilian I |date=2019 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-1-58839-674-7 |page=302 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X-anDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA302 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[1504]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Bullinger]], Swiss pastor and reformer (d. 1575)<ref>https://data.bnf.fr/en/12029437/heinrich_bullinger/</ref>\n*[[1534]] &ndash; [[Zacharius Ursinus]], German theologian (d. 1583)<ref>https://data.bnf.fr/en/12111417/zacharias_ursinus/</ref>\n*[[1552]] &ndash; [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor|Rudolf II]], Holy Roman Emperor (d. 1612)<ref>{{cite web |title=Rudolf II {{!}} Holy Roman emperor |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Rudolf-II-Holy-Roman-emperor |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[1634]] &ndash; [[Johannes Camphuys]], Dutch politician, [[Governor-General of the Dutch East Indies]] (d. 1695)\n*[[1659]] &ndash; [[Hyacinthe Rigaud]], French painter (d. 1743)\n*[[1670]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Bononcini]], Italian cellist and composer (d. 1747)\n*[[1702]] &ndash; [[Maria Clementina Sobieska]], Polish noble (d. 1735)\n*[[1718]] &ndash; [[Saverio Bettinelli]], Italian poet, playwright, and critic (d. 1808)\n*[[1720]] &ndash; [[Gilbert White]], English ornithologist and ecologist (d. 1793)<ref>{{Cite DNB|wstitle=White, Gilbert|last=Newton|first=Alfred|authorlink=Alfred Newton|volume=61}}</ref>\n*[[1724]] &ndash; [[Duchess Maria Antonia of Bavaria|Maria Antonia of Bavaria]], Electress of Saxony (d. 1780)\n*[[1750]] &ndash; [[Prince Frederick Adolf of Sweden|Frederick Adolf]], duke of \u00d6sterg\u00f6tland (d. 1803)\n*[[1796]] &ndash; [[Immanuel Hermann Fichte]], German philosopher and academic (d. 1879)\n*[[1811]] &ndash; [[William Makepeace Thackeray]], English author and poet (d. 1863)\n*[[1818]] &ndash; [[Louis Gerhard De Geer]], Swedish lawyer and politician, 1st [[Prime Minister of Sweden]] (d. 1896)\n*[[1821]] &ndash; [[Pauline Viardot]], French soprano and composer (d. 1910)\n*[[1837]] &ndash; [[Vasil Levski]], Bulgarian priest and activist (d. 1873)\n*[[1843]] &ndash; [[Virgil Earp]], American marshal (d. 1905)\n*[[1845]] &ndash; [[Tristan Corbi\u00e8re]], French poet (d. 1875)\n*[[1848]] &ndash; [[W. G. Grace]], English cricketer and physician (d. 1915)\n*[[1853]] &ndash; [[Hendrik Lorentz]], Dutch physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1928)\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[Kadambini Ganguly]], Indian physician, one of the first Indian women to obtain a degree (d. 1923)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scienceandculture-isna.org/sep-oct-2014/07%20Art_Kadambini%20Ganguly...by_B%20K%20Sen_Pg.271.pdf|title=\"KADAMBINI GANGULY \u2013 AN ILLUSTRIOUS LADY\"|last=SEN|first=B.K.|website=Science and Culture - Indian Science News Organization.}}</ref> \n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden]], English politician, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] (d. 1937)\n*[[1867]] &ndash; [[Margaret Brown]], American philanthropist and activist (d. 1932)\n*[[1871]] &ndash; [[Giacomo Balla]], Italian painter (d.1958)\n*  1871   &ndash; [[Sada Yacco]], Japanese actress and dancer (d. 1946)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Larry McLean]], Canadian-American baseball player (d. 1921)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[Alberto di Jorio]], Italian cardinal (d. 1979)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Simon Bolivar Buckner Jr.]], American general (d. 1945)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[Vidkun Quisling]], Norwegian military officer and politician, [[List of heads of government of Norway|Minister President of Norway]] (d. 1945)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[K\u014dichi Kido]], Japanese politician, 13th [[Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal of Japan]] (d. 1977)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Frank Forde]], Australian educator and politician, 15th [[Prime Minister of Australia]] (d. 1983)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Arthur Friedenreich]], Brazilian footballer (d. 1969)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[David Ogilvy, 12th Earl of Airlie]], Scottish peer, soldier and courtier (d. 1968)\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Olga Spessivtseva]], Russian-American ballerina (d. 1991)\n*  1895   &ndash; [[Machine Gun Kelly]], American gangster (d. 1954)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Ernest Eldridge]], English race car driver and engineer (d. 1935)\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[John Stuart (actor)|John Stuart]],